ber<br>
of tools to try to stay secure from the NSA. The advice I shared included<b=
r>
using Tor, preferring certain cryptography over others, and using<br>
public-domain encryption wherever possible.<br>
<br>
I also recommended using an air gap, which physically isolates a computer o=
r<br>
local network of computers from the internet. (The name comes from the<br>
literal gap of air between the computer and the internet; the word predates=
<br>
wireless networks.)<br>
<br>
But this is more complicated than it sounds, and requires explanation.<br>
<br>
Since we know that computers connected to the internet are vulnerable to<br=
>
outside hacking, an air gap should protect against those attacks. There are=
 a<br>
lot of systems that use =97 or should use =97 air gaps: classified military=
<br>
networks, nuclear power plant controls, medical equipment, avionics, and so=
<br>
on.<br>
<br>
Osama Bin Laden used one. I hope human rights organizations in repressive<b=
r>
countries are doing the same.<br>
<br>
Air gaps might be conceptually simple, but they=92re hard to maintain in<br=
>
practice. The truth is that nobody wants a computer that never receives fil=
es<br>
from the internet and never sends files out into the internet. What they wa=
nt<br>
is a computer that=92s not directly connected to the internet, albeit with =
some<br>
secure way of moving files on and off.<br>
<br>
But every time a file moves back or forth, there=92s the potential for atta=
ck.<br>
<br>
And air gaps have been breached. Stuxnet was a U.S. and Israeli<br>
military-grade piece of malware that attacked the Natanz nuclear plant in<b=
r>
Iran. It successfully jumped the air gap and penetrated the Natanz network.=
<br>
Another piece of malware named agent.btz, probably Chinese in origin,<br>
successfully jumped the air gap protecting U.S. military networks.<br>
<br>
These attacks work by exploiting security vulnerabilities in the removable<=
br>
media used to transfer files on and off the air gapped computers.<br>
<br>
Bruce Schneier is a security technologist and author. His latest book is<br=
>
Liars and Outliers: Enabling the Trust Society Needs to Survive.<br>
<br>
Since working with Snowden=92s NSA files, I have tried to maintain a single=
<br>
air-gapped computer. It turned out to be harder than I expected, and I have=
<br>
ten rules for anyone trying to do the same:<br>
<br>
1. When you set up your computer, connect it to the internet as little as<b=
r>
possible. It=92s impossible to completely avoid connecting the computer to =
the<br>
internet, but try to configure it all at once and as anonymously as possibl=
e.<br>
I purchased my computer off-the-shelf in a big box store, then went to a<br=
>
friend=92s network and downloaded everything I needed in a single session. =
(The<br>
ultra-paranoid way to do this is to buy two identical computers, configure<=
br>
one using the above method, upload the results to a cloud-based anti-virus<=
br>
checker, and transfer the results of that to the air gap machine using a<br=
>
one-way process.)<br>
<br>
2. Install the minimum software set you need to do your job, and disable al=
l<br>
operating system services that you won=92t need. The less software you inst=
all,<br>
the less an attacker has available to exploit. I downloaded and installed<b=
r>
OpenOffice, a PDF reader, a text editor, TrueCrypt, and BleachBit. That=92s=
<br>
all. (No, I don=92t have any inside knowledge about TrueCrypt, and there=92=
s a<br>
lot about it that makes me suspicious. But for Windows full-disk encryption=
<br>
it=92s that, Microsoft=92s BitLocker, or Symantec=92s PGPDisk =97 and I am =
more<br>
worried about large U.S. corporations being pressured by the NSA than I am<=
br>
about TrueCrypt.)<br>
<br>
3. Once you have your computer configured, never directly connect it to the=
<br>
internet again. Consider physically disabling the wireless capability, so i=
t<br>
doesn=92t get turned on by accident.<br>
<br>
4. If you need to install new software, download it anonymously from a rand=
om<br>
network, put it on some removable media, and then manually transfer it to t=
he<br>
air gapped computer. This is by no means perfect, but it=92s an attempt to =
make<br>
it harder for the attacker to target your computer.<br>
<br>
5. Turn off all auto-run features. This should be standard practice for all=
<br>
the computers you own, but it=92s especially important for an air-gapped<br=
>
computer. Agent.btz used autorun to infect U.S. military computers.<br>
<br>
6. Minimize the amount of executable code you move onto the air-gapped<br>
computer. Text files are best. Microsoft Office files and PDFs are more<br>
dangerous, since they might have embedded macros. Turn off all macro<br>
capabilities you can on the air-gapped computer. Don=92t worry too much abo=
ut<br>
patching your system; in general, the risk of the executable code is worse<=
br>
than the risk of not having your patches up to date. You=92re not on the<br=
>
internet, after all.<br>
<br>
7. Only use trusted media to move files on and off air-gapped computers. A<=
br>
USB stick you purchase from a store is safer than one given to you by someo=
ne<br>
you don=92t know =97 or one you find in a parking lot.<br>
<br>
8. For file transfer, a writable optical disk (CD or DVD) is safer than a U=
SB<br>
stick. Malware can silently write data to a USB stick, but it can=92t spin =
the<br>
CD-R up to 1000 rpm without your noticing. This means that the malware can<=
br>
only write to the disk when you write to the disk. You can also verify how<=
br>
much data has been written to the CD by physically checking the back of it.=
<br>
If you=92ve only written one file, but it looks like three-quarters of the =
CD<br>
was burned, you have a problem. Note: the first company to market a USB sti=
ck<br>
with a light that indicates a write operation =97 not read or write; I=92ve=
 got<br>
one of those =97 wins a prize.<br>
<br>
9. When moving files on and off your air-gapped computer, use the absolute<=
br>
smallest storage device you can. And fill up the entire device with random<=
br>
files. If an air-gapped computer is compromised, the malware is going to tr=
y<br>
to sneak data off it using that media. While malware can easily hide stolen=
<br>
files from you, it can=92t break the laws of physics. So if you use a tiny<=
br>
transfer device, it can only steal a very small amount of data at a time. I=
f<br>
you use a large device, it can take that much more. Business-card-sized<br>
mini-CDs can have capacity as low as 30 MB. I still see 1-GB USB sticks for=
<br>
sale.<br>
<br>
10. Consider encrypting everything you move on and off the air-gapped<br>
computer. Sometimes you=92ll be moving public files and it won=92t matter, =
but<br>
sometimes you won=92t be, and it will. And if you=92re using optical media,=
 those<br>
disks will be impossible to erase. Strong encryption solves these problems.=
<br>
And don=92t forget to encrypt the computer as well; whole-disk encryption i=
s<br>
the best.<br>
<br>
One thing I didn=92t do, although it=92s worth considering, is use a statel=
ess<br>
operating system like Tails. You can configure Tails with a persistent volu=
me<br>
